hands_on_practices.solution:
The deformation is given by $x_{1}=\lambda_{1}X_{1}$, $x_{2}=\lambda_{2}X_{2}$, $x_{3}=\lambda_{3}X_{3}$. The deformation gradient tensor $\mathbf{F}$ has components $F_{iJ}=\frac{\partial x_{i}}{\partial X_{J}}$. Computing the partial derivatives yields
$$
\mathbf{F}=\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{\partial x_{1}}{\partial X_{1}} & \frac{\partial x_{1}}{\partial X_{2}} & \frac{\partial x_{1}}{\partial X_{3}}\\
\frac{\partial x_{2}}{\partial X_{1}} & \frac{\partial x_{2}}{\partial X_{2}} & \frac{\partial x_{2}}{\partial X_{3}}\\
\frac{\partial x_{3}}{\partial X_{1}} & \frac{\partial x_{3}}{\partial X_{2}} & \frac{\partial x_{3}}{\partial X_{3}}
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
\lambda_{1} & 0 & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2} & 0\\
0 & 0 & \lambda_{3}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
The left Cauchy-Green deformation tensor is defined by $\mathbf{B}=\mathbf{F} \mathbf{F}^{T}$. Since $\mathbf{F}$ is diagonal, $\mathbf{F}^{T}=\mathbf{F}$ and the product gives
$$
\mathbf{B}=\mathbf{F} \mathbf{F}^{T}=\begin{pmatrix}
\lambda_{1} & 0 & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2} & 0\\
0 & 0 & \lambda_{3}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\lambda_{1} & 0 & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2} & 0\\
0 & 0 & \lambda_{3}
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
\lambda_{1}^{2} & 0 & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2}^{2} & 0\\
0 & 0 & \lambda_{3}^{2}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Thus, the matrix representation of $\mathbf{B}$ is diagonal with entries $\lambda_{1}^{2}$, $\lambda_{2}^{2}$, and $\lambda_{3}^{2}$.
